,"1328":"1328","Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England","Scotland":"Schotland","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Berwickshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Yester, Haddingtonshire, Schotland","Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1331–1382":"1331–1382","1328–1369":"1328–1369","1352–1439":"1352–1439","1298–1364":"1298–1364","1305–1386":"1305–1386","1352":"1352","15 March 1369":"15 March 1369","1382":"1382","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1369":"1369","1453":"1453","1331":"1331","1364":"1364","1386":"1386","1298":"1298","1439":"1439","about 1351":"about 1351","1328":"1328","Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England","Scotland":"Scotland","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vaux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of various places in northern France called Vaux, from the Old French plural of <i>val</i> ‘valley’. Compare English   Vause   and French   Devaux  .","History: Richard Vaux (1749–90) emigrated from Sussex, England, to Philadelphia, PA, in early youth. Calvert Vaux, landscape architect, emigrated from London, England, to America in 1850 and designed several major US parks, including Central Park in New York City (with Frederick Olmstead). — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its variant <i>Veaux</i> and altered form   Devoe  ) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Vause","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire):","of Norman origin, a habitational name from Vaux (see   Vaux  ), a common French placename, singular and plural of <i>val</i> ‘valley’, the plural form being Latinized in surnames as <i>de Vallibus</i>. Norman lords with this surname are recorded in 12th- and early 13th-century records in Cumberland (Irthington), Devon (Farwood, in Colyton), East Yorkshire (Warter), Essex (Belchamp), and Leicestershire (Belvoir). Compare   Vale  .","nickname perhaps from Middle English <i>fals</i>, <i>faus</i>, <i>vaus</i> (Old French <i>fals</i>, <i>faus</i>, Old English <i>fals</i>) ‘deceitful, disloyal, dishonest, mendacious’, but it is more likely the name arises from 1, with the common Anglo-Norman French substitution of <i>le</i> for <i>de</i> in their surname."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":6,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":51,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Vaux was born in 1331, in Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, her father, William de Vaux - Lord of Direlton, was 33 and her mother, Catherine Douglas, was 26. She married Sir John Lyle about 1351, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1382, in Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1331–1382":"1331–1382","1328–1369":"1328–1369","1352–1439":"1352–1439","1298–1364":"1298–1364","1305–1386":"1305–1386","1352":"1352","15 March 1369":"15. märts 1369","1382":"1382","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1369":"1369","1453":"1453","1331":"1331","1364":"1364","1386":"1386","1298":"1298","1439":"1439","about 1351":"umbes 1351","1328":"1328","Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England","Scotland":"Scotland","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Berwickshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1331–1382":"1331–1382","1328–1369":"1328–1369","1352–1439":"1352–1439","1298–1364":"1298–1364","1305–1386":"1305–1386","1352":"1352","15 March 1369":